
[1]hammer

   HAM'MER, n. An instrument for driving nails, beating metals, and the
   like. It consists of an iron head, fixed crosswise to a handle. Hammers
   are of various sizes; a large hammer used by smiths is called a sledge.

   HAM'MER, v.t. To beat with a hammer; as, to hammer iron or steel.

   1. To form or forge with a hammer; to shape by beating.

   2. To work in the mind; to contrive by intellectual labor; usually with
   out; as, to hammer out a scheme.

         HAM'MER, v.i. To work; to be busy; to labor in contrivance.

   1. To be working or in agitation.
